Description of Investigation

  2. Scope and nature of this Report

This Report summarizes the results of the legal due diligence activities conducted by BonelliErede from 30 August to 23 October 2023 in favour of the Client, in connection with the Envisaged Transaction.

Our investigation is strictly limited to legal matters and is not to be read as extending by implication to any other matter, including any other matter that may be material to the recipients. The authors do not accept any responsibility for reviewing or reporting on any financial, commercial or technical implications of the information they reviewed, although they did seek, where possible, to highlight matters that seemed to be financially, commercially or technically relevant. However, the criteria on which they have judged significance may differ from those that would be applied from a financial, commercial or technical perspective.

No representation is made, nor should any implication be made or conclusion drawn, regarding the fact that the issues or information summarised or the notes provided in this Report constitute, individually or in the aggregate, all material information relating to the legal due diligence investigation conducted or the matters addressed in the specific note or, in any event, all material information that a potential investor may wish to know in investigating the Envisaged Transaction.

The sole purpose of this Report is to assist the Client in the evaluation of the Envisaged Transaction. As such, this Report was prepared for informational purposes only and on the express understanding that it will be used only for those purposes.

This Report is not a legal opinion or a legal or regulatory compliance audit on the subject matter and must not be regarded as a substitute for specific legal advice on the matters covered in this Report.

This Report is subject to the limitations and assumptions set out in the final pages.

  1.  DD Dashboard

As instructed by the Client, this Report was prepared with a red-flag approach and therefore contains only a brief summary of certain key findings or key elements that, in the authors’ view, may be material in the context of the Envisaged Transaction, rather than a full, detailed description and analysis of the Reviewed Documentation. However, our analysis also extended to all the Reviewed Documentation and, more specifically, to all the main information listed under Annex C – DD Dashboard – Agricom Main Data and Annex D – DD Dashboard – D&G Main Data, which should be considered as an integral and essential part of the Report and may include additional findings.

  1. Risk Levels Sections

This Report is divides in sections classified based on the risk level assessment (“RLA”) that the authors made concerning a specific issue.

The RLA is not a substitute for specific legal advice on how to mitigate or resolve each relevant issue. The RLA is merely a figurative representation of the potential risk level of each relevant issue with regard only to the Envisaged Transaction.

Below is a Legenda of the risk level sections:

High Risk: The High-Risk Section includes only findings or issues impacting the transaction’s structure and that should be carefully considered by the Client in assessing the Envisaged Transaction.

Low Risk/No Risk: The Low-Risk/No Risk Section includes only findings to be considered by the Client in consideration of the Company’s business or in the general context of the Envisaged Transaction, without including a summary or a complete list of all documents analyzed.

Medium Risk: The Medium-Risk Section includes only findings or issues that requires in-depth analysis, or to be covered with special indemnities or other contractual protections or only be considered in the general context of the Envisaged Transaction.

Triggered Events: This Section includes only the provisions or events which may be triggered by the Envisaged Transaction (e.g., change of control clauses, duty to inform etc.).

Agricom – Credem loan agreements – transfer of shares ban

Agricom and Credito Emiliano S.p.A. (“Credem”) entered into the following loan agreements on, respectively:

28 October 2020 for EUR 300,000 – this agreement is covered by a “consortium guarantee” (i.e., “fondo di garanzia per le PMI”) that secures up to 90% of the loan principal; and

25 July 2023 for EUR 1,000,000.

These agreements provide, among other things, that Agricom’s quota-holders may not transfer their quotas to people or groups other than those who already own Agricom’s quotas on the date of the relevant loan agreement. Credem may terminate the relevant agreement if Agricom breaches this obligation.

We suggest considering whether to include in the Agreement an undertaking from Seller to ensure that Agricom obtains the waiver from Credem of its right to terminate the relevant agreement upon completion of the Envisaged Transaction.

Agricom – Banca Valsabbina and BCC loan agreements – duty-to-inform provisions

Banca Valsabbina loan agreement

On 23 October 2018, Agricom and Banca Valsabbina S.C.P.A. (“Banca Valsabbina”) entered into a loan agreement for EUR 400,000, that expires on 22 April 2024. This agreement is covered by a “consortium guarantee” that secures up to 80% of the loan principal.

This agreement envisages, among other things, that Agricom must notify Banca Valsabbina at least 90 days before carrying out any “extraordinary transactions”. Banca Valsabbina may terminate this agreement if Agricom breaches this obligation.

BCC loan agreement

On 2 December 2020, Agricom and Banca di Credito Cooperativo Pordenonese Monsile S.C. (“BCC”) entered into a loan agreement for EUR 300,000, that expires on 2 December 2026. This agreement is covered by: (i) a “consortium guarantee” that secures up to 90% of the loan principal; and (ii) a personal guarantee issued by the Seller that secures the entire loan principal.

This agreement envisages, among other things, that Agricom must notify BCC promptly of any changes to its shareholding structure. BCC may terminate this agreement if Agricom breaches this obligation.

Although some provisions have rather broad content (i.e., Banca Valsabbina loan’s provision), we suggest considering whether to include in the Agreement an appropriate mechanism to ensure Agricom’s compliance with these duty-to-inform undertakings.

Agricom – financial lease agreements with MPS Leasing – duty-to-inform provisions

Agricom and MPS Leasing & Factoring S.p.A. (“MPS Leasing”) entered into the following 60-month term financial lease agreements on, respectively:

21 December 2020 for EUR 28,700; and

21 December 2020 for EUR 26,800.

These agreements provide, among other things, that Agricom must promptly notify MPS Leasing of any changes to the company’s ownership. MPS Leasing may terminate the relevant agreement if Agricom breaches this obligation.

Although the loans have a negligible amount, we suggest considering whether to include in the Agreement an appropriate mechanism to ensure Agricom’s compliance with these duty-to-inform undertakings.

D&G – Iccrea and BCC Leasing financial lease agreements – duty-to-inform provisions

Iccrea financial lease agreements

D&G and ICCREA Banca Impresa S.p.A. (“Iccrea”) entered into 6 financial lease agreements with 60-month term.

Under these agreements, D&G must promptly notify Iccrea of any: (i) ‘corporate change’, incl. any preliminary deeds for a transformation, merger, demerger, contribution, transfer, or lease of a business unit or going concern; and (ii) changes to the company’s ‘composition or representation’. Iccrea may terminate the relevant agreement if D&G breaches this obligation.

BCC Leasing financial lease agreements

D&G and BCC Leasing S.p.A. (“BCC Leasing”) entered into 2 financial lease agreements with 60-month term.

Under these agreements, D&G must promptly notify BCC Leasing of any: (i) ‘corporate change’, incl. any preliminary deeds for a transformation, merger, demerger, contribution, transfer, or lease of a business unit or going concern; and (ii) changes to the company’s ‘composition or representation’. BCC Leasing may terminate the relevant agreement if D&G breaches this obligation.

We suggest considering whether to include in the Agreement an appropriate mechanism to ensure D&G’s compliance with these duty-to-inform undertakings.

D&G – MCC financial lease agreement – changes in the quota-holding structure

D&G and Mediocredito Italiano S.p.A. (“MCC”) entered into a financial lease agreement for EUR 169,107.12 on 21 December 2018, that expires on 31 January 2024.

This agreement envisages, among other things, that MCC may withdraw from the agreement in the event of D&G’s significant changes to its quota-holding structure.

We suggest considering whether to include in the Agreement an undertaking from Seller to ensure that D&G obtains a waiver from MCC of its right to withdraw from the agreement upon completion of the Envisaged Transaction.

Incorporation of the related parties Ama-Zonia and IG

Based on the Reviewed Documentation, we understand the following:

On 28 July 2020, the Agricom quota-holder’s meeting approved the partial and proportional demerger of Agricom by transferring part of its assets to a newly incorporated company, Ama-Zonia (whose sole quota-holder is Giorgio Daniel). The objective for this demerger was to reorganise the wood waste storage, processing and trading businesses. Based on the Reviewed Documentation (i.e., summary document, copies of the demerger project and the relevant notarial deed dated 7 October 2020), we understand that the “wood going concern” comprised: (i) a supply agreement with a buyer/intermediary of wood sawdust; (ii) a piece of machinery; (iii) various equipment; (iv) a lease agreement for the warehouse where the business is carried out; (v) a “wood waste” treatment licence; and (vi) 1–2 employees.

On 28 June 2021, the Agricom quota-holder’s meeting approved the partial and proportional demerger of Agricom by transferring part of its assets to a newly incorporated company, IG (whose sole quota-holder is Giorgio Daniel). The objective for this demerger was to structurally separate the real estate properties from the company’s core business. Based on the summary document uploaded to the VDR (i.e., summary document, copies of the demerger project and the relevant notarial deed dated 30 July 2021), we understand that this “real estate going concern” comprised: (i) properties in Fossalta di Piave and Anghiari; (ii) generic systems relating to the properties; (iii) loan agreements for the purchase of these properties; (iv) a real estate financial lease agreement for another building in Fossalta di Piave; and (v) maintenance and improvements on the leased properties.

We suggest evaluating whether to include a special indemnity to cover any potential risks that could arise from the joint and several liability of Agricom with Ama-Zonia and IG in the context of the relevant demerger.

Agricom – Non-compete covenant binding a key employee

NCC binding a key Agricom employee

The Reviewed Documentation includes a copy of a non-compete covenant (“NCC”) dated 17 November 2020 that binds a key Agricom employee (whose name appears to have been redacted) and has the following main provisions:

Subject matter: the employee must not carry out activities in competition with Agricom in any way or form.

Term: 1 year after termination of the employment relationship.

Territory: Italy.

Consideration: EUR 600 per month, paid monthly during the employment relationship in 14 instalments per year.

Penalty: if the employee breaches the NCC, he must refund all amounts received as consideration and he must pay a penalty of EUR 50,000, without prejudice to Agricom’s right to claim further damages.

However, we have received a copy of another NCC binding the above key employee that is dated 1 February 2023 and that, according to the Received Information, replaces the above NCC dated 17 November 2020.

This new NCC contains the same T&Cs as the old NCC, except that it provides for consideration of EUR 2,000 per month, paid during the employment relationship in 12 instalments per year.

Considering the above, because the remuneration is paid during employment a risk exists of this NCC being considered void, in line with certain Italian caselaw (whereby payment in instalments during employment renders the remuneration undetermined and undeterminable because it depends on the employment term).

However, according to other caselaw – incl. recent caselaw – payment during employment is lawful but the amount paid overall needs to be adequate considering the scope of the covenant. In the case at hand, considering that the duration of the non-compete obligations is not particularly long and the geographical area to which the NCC applies is limited to Italy, the consideration appears to be adequate (as it represents approx. 50% of the employee’s gross annual salary).[12]

NCC binding another Agricom employee:

The Reviewed Documentation also includes a copy of a NCC that binds another Agricom employee and has the following main provisions:

Subject matter: the employee must not carry out activities in competition with Agricom in any way or form.

Term: 3 years after termination of the employment relationship.

Territory: Italy.

Penalty: if the employee breaches the NCC, he must refund all amounts received as consideration and he must pay a penalty of EUR 20,000, without prejudice to Agricom’s right to claim further damages.

This NCC envisages no consideration for the employee’s non-compete obligations. This is one of the specific requirements for an NCC under Art. 2125 of the Italian Civil Code and breach of this requirement renders an NCC void. However, according to the Received Information, Agricom pays this employee EUR 1,200 per month as consideration for this NCC.

Agricom informed us (through the Q&A Process) that, despite numerous solicitations, this employee did not sign the NCC. However, according to the Received Information, this is because this employee has forgotten to do so (which Agricom will try to remedy as soon as possible) and not because of the employee’s refusal to sign the NCC.

Considering the above, a risk exists of this NCC being considered void because: (i) this employee has not signed the agreement (in this case the employee would be free to carry out activities in competition with Agricom, but he would have to return the received NCC consideration as it would lack legal title) and; (ii) the consideration is paid during employment – in line with certain caselaw (see above).[13]

According to the Received Information, there are no other Agricom employees bound by NCCs.

Because these NCCs may be considered void, if the Client is interested in maintaining the current non-competition obligations, we suggest considering to amend (with the employees’ agreement) the existing NCC upon the closing date.

Additionally, we suggest ensuring that the employee signs his NCC.

Agricom – Consultancy contract on a continuative and coordinated basis

The Reviewed Documentation includes 1 consultancy contract on a continuative and coordinated basis (contratto di collaborazione coordinata e continuativa) entered into by Agricom with an individual for the management of biogas and livestock operations at Agricom’s premises (more specifically, this consultant assesses the performance and productivity of incoming and outgoing products, develops and manages the sales network, identifies growth strategies and monitors the production process).

From a formal standpoint, the above contract envisages that:

the consultant’s activities are normally carried out at Agricom offices, however the activities may be also carried out at the consultant’s or the company’s clients’ premises, depending on the operational needs indicated by Agricom from time to time; and

Agricom undertakes to provide the consultant with: (i) a workstation at company’s offices; (ii) a telephone; (iii) a laptop, and (iv) a car.

From a substantive standpoint, in principle if self-employment relationships involve the performance of professional services that are mainly personal, continuous and organised by the principal (i.e., the principal decides how the work is performed, inc. place of work and working hours), both the consultant and the Italian Social Security Authority (“INPS”, Istituto Nazionale per la Previdenza Sociale) could claim the application of Art. 2 of Legislative Decree 81/2015 which stipulates that the rules governing employment relationships apply to self-employment relationships that display all the above elements simultaneously. This entails the following consequences:

  • the consultant is entitled to the protection granted to permanent employees by law and by the applicable national collective bargaining agreement (minimum wage, statutory end-of-service benefit, etc.); and
  • Agricom may have to pay social security contributions at the higher rates due for employees and penalties for not having paid these contributions previously.

According to the Received Information concerning the substantive performance methods of this relationship: (i) Agricom does not issue the consultant instructions or directives on how and when the work activity is to be performed, does not exercise disciplinary powers over the consultant, does not set his working hours and does not require the consultant to justify any absences or tardiness; and (ii) the consultant has other clients besides Agricom. However, Agricom assigns this consultant a company email account and a workstation at the company’s premises.

In light of the above, we cannot exclude the above risk, although it may be less material if and to the extent that the consultant – as per the Received Information – is effectively not subject to Agricom directions/control/disciplinary powers and actually operates autonomously.

We suggest ensuring that the set of R&Ws in the Agreement covers this matter.

Nevertheless, we suggest considering whether to include a special indemnity covering any loss arising from the recharacterisation of this individual as an employee.

Agricom – Variable remuneration

According to the Reviewed Documentation and the Received Information, 11 Agricom employees are entitled to an annual bonus (generally paid in October) upon achievement of individual and company targets.

We have received copies of the assignment letters of the FY 2022-23 bonus to all the above 11 employees. This bonus will be paid by October 2023, and it ranges from EUR 600 to 4,000 depending on the employee, except for the general manager’s bonus which amounts to max. EUR 40,000.

According to the Received Information, Agricom does not consider the amount of the above bonus when calculating the employees’ statutory end-of-service benefit (“TFR”, Trattamento di Fine Rapporto).

Under Italian law and the National Collective Bargaining Agreement for Employees in the Trade Sector (“NCBA Trade”), non-occasional indemnities must be considered when calculating the employees’ TFR.

Because the abovementioned bonus paid to Agricom’s employees is non-occasional, it should be considered for determining TFR. Therefore, Agricom appears to have breached this rule and this could entail the risk that, upon termination of their relationships, the employees could claim a payment from Agricom corresponding to the amount of TFR not calculated (7.4% of the payable amount, plus accrued interest) and, therefore, not paid out.

We suggest inserting adequate protections in the Agreement (e.g., special indemnities).

As for the future, we suggest regularizing the situation by including the variable remuneration when calculating the TFR.

D&G – Variable remuneration

According to the Reviewed Documentation and the Received Information, 1 D&G employee is entitled to a bonus in recognition of individual performance targets.

The FY 2022-23 bonus is paid by October 2023, and it corresponds to 1.50% of D&G’s gross profit before tax as of 31 August 2023, calculated starting from 1 March 2023.[14]

Moreover, considering the employee on-call availability 7 days a week, starting from October 2023 he is granted EUR 150 per month.

According to the Received Information, D&G does not consider the amount of the above bonus when calculating the employee’s TFR.

Under Italian law and the National Collective Bargaining Agreement for employees of road transport, logistics and shipping companies (Contratto Collettivo Nazionale di Lavoro Autotrasporto Merci e Logistica), all non-occasional sums paid in connection with the employment relationship must be considered when determining the TFR, therefore D&G appears to have breached the above rule.

This would entail the risk that, upon termination of his/her relationship, this employee could claim a payment from D&G corresponding to the amount of TFR not calculated (7.4% of the payable amount, plus accrued interest) and, therefore, not paid out.

We suggest inserting adequate protections in the Agreement (e.g., special indemnities).

As for the future, we suggest regularizing the situation by including the variable remuneration when calculating the TFR.

D&G – Overtime

According to the Reviewed Documentation, in FYs 2021-22 the following number of D&G employees exceeded the maximum annual overtime hours permitted under the NCBA Trade (i.e., 250 hours):

2022: 12 employees; and

2021: 13 employees.

In light of the above, D&G could be subject to the administrative fines for overtime hours exceeding the legal limit (of EUR 154–1,032, considering that the breach involved more than 5 employees).

We suggest inserting appropriate R&Ws and/or other adequate protections in the Agreement (e.g., special indemnities).

D&G – Accrued and untaken holidays

Although we can only make a rough calculation, based on the Reviewed Documentation it appears that 4 D&G employees had accrued and untaken holidays exceeding the legal limit as at June 2023.

In light of the above, D&G could be subject to the administrative fine of EUR 120–720 (as the breach involved fewer than 5 employees).

We suggest inserting appropriate R&Ws and/or other adequate protections in the Agreement (e.g., special indemnities).

Agricom – Accidents at work

According to the Reviewed Documentation and the Received Information, 2 accidents at work occurred in FY 2023 that resulted in an absence from work exceeding 40 days (i.e., 100 and 87 days of absence, respectively).

According to the Received Information, to date there are no pending or threatened disputes with these employees or the Italian Insurance Authority for Accidents at Work (INAIL, Istituto Nazionale Assicurazione Infortuni sul Lavoro) or any other authority related to these accidents.

We suggest inserting appropriate R&Ws and/or other adequate protections in the Agreement (e.g., special indemnities).

Agricom – Mandatory hirings

The Reviewed Documentation includes Agricom’s annual hiring charts (prospetti informativi) for FYs 2018–19 that were sent to the labour authorities. These show that in FY 2018 Agricom was in breach of its obligation to hire 1 disabled employee.

According to the Received Information: (i) the annual chart for FY 2020 was not sent because in that year Agricom employed less than 15 employees and therefore it was not subject to mandatory hiring obligations; and (ii) from FY 2021 Agricom requested to entered into an agreement with I Tigli 2 Società Cooperativa Sociale.[15]

We have received copies of 2 agreements entered into by Agricom with I Tigli 2 Società Cooperativa Sociale for FYs 2022 and 2023, each with a duration of 1 year, for the employment of 1 disabled person (equal to 100% of the mandatory quota).

Considering the above single vacancy in FY 2018 and the fact that, based on the Received Information it appears that in FY 2021 the company did not send the annual hiring chart, and that we received no copy of any agreement for 2021, we cannot exclude the risk of Agricom being subject to administrative fines for having breached mandatory hiring rules.[16]

We suggest inserting appropriate R&Ws and/or other adequate protections in the Agreement (e.g., special indemnities).

Agricom – uncertainty on ownership of the Patents

Agricom owns the following patent applications (“Patents”):[17]

no. 102023000009642, “Impianto di essicazione”, filed on 12 May 2023 in Italy;

no. 102023000017868, “Impianto di macinazione”, filed on 30 August 2023;

no. 102023000017871, “Impianto di vuotamento di vasetti”, filed on 30 August 2023; and

no. 102023000017874, “Impianto di sconfezionamento di prodotti alimentari confezionati”, filed on 30 August 2023.

The inventor of the patents for the above applications is Giorgio Daniel, sole director and quota-holder of Agricom.

We were informed that the inventive activities carried out by Giorgio Daniel are not regulated by a specific agreement between the inventor and Agricom. In the absence of a specific agreement, we therefore cannot exclude the risk of Giorgio Daniel claiming ownership of the intellectual property rights over the Patents.

Given the uncertainty of this situation, we suggest obtaining a written declaration from Giorgio Daniel, to be countersigned by Agricom for acceptance, whereby he:

transfers all IP rights over the Patents to Agricom; and

declares that he has no claims over the Patents (incl. economic claims) and waives promoting such claims towards Agricom in future.

Agricom’s material R&D projects – uncertainty regarding the ownership of the results and risk of employees claiming a “fair reward”

According to the Received Information, the most important R&D projects carried out by Agricom that relate to Agricom’s production process are the following:

R&D carried out by individuals

Under Italian Law, intellectual property rights over employees’ and external consultants’ inventions belong to the employer (i.e., Agricom) only if the inventive activity is specifically envisaged under the relevant employment or consultancy agreement. If not, the intellectual property rights belong to the employee or to the external consultant.[20]

Also, under Italian law, if employees develop inventions during and within the scope of their employment and receive no specific remuneration for their inventive activity, they are entitled to a “fair reward” (equo premio) from the employer if the employer obtains a patent or uses the results as trade secrets.[21]

According to the Reviewed Documentation, Clelia Daniel is employed as a “sustainability manager” and Giovanni De Nardi is employed as a “mechanical blue-collar employee”. Inventive activity is not envisaged as the object under their respective employment contracts and is not specifically remunerated.

Additionally – as mentioned in the “Patent” box above – the R&D carried out by Giorgio Daniel is not governed by a specific contract entered with Agricom.

For all the above reasons: (i) we are unable to confirm that Agricom owns all intellectual property rights over the results of the R&D carried out by its employees and by Giorgio Daniel; and (ii) if Agricom decides to file patent applications[22] or uses the results of these R&D activities under a secrecy regime, we cannot exclude the risk of these employees (i.e., Clelia Daniel and Giovanni De Nardi) claiming a “fair reward” (equo premio) from Agricom.

R&D carried out by Company 3

We reviewed several R&D contracts in the VDR between Agricom and contractors whose names are all redacted. We received an unclear response to our request (through the Q&A Process) for clarification as to which contract governs the R&D projects carried out with Company 3.

More specifically, the Company referred to only 1 contract (VDR ref. “IP-A-12.10-Contratto di consulenza Società 3 09_01_17_(Firmato) + Allegati”), but it appears that Agricom entered into 2 separate contracts with Company 3. However, both these 2 agreements have the same object (i.e., the design and construction of electrical plants) and envisage that the IP rights over the results of the R&D projects are owned by Agricom[23].

Techincal drawings provided by Elettrotek S.n.c. (“Elettrotek”)

According to the Received Information, the drawings attached to the R&D contracts with Company 3 that relate to the electrical plants were prepared by a third party (Elettrotek) in the absence of a written agreement. Due to the lack of documentation addressing the governance on the IP rights among the parties, a risk exists that Elettrotek may claim ownership of IP rights on such technical drawings towards Agricom.

Given the uncertainty of this situation, we suggest obtaining a written declaration from: (a) the employees involved in R&D; and (b) Giorgio Daniel, whereby they declare that:

all IP rights over the results of the R&D projects belong to Agricom; and

they have no claims over the results of the R&D projects (incl. economic claims) and waive promoting such claims towards Agricom in future.

In addition, if the business relationship with Elettrotek is still ongoing, we suggest obtaining a written declaration from Elettotek representatives confirming that all the IP rights over the technical drawings provided by Elettrotek exclusively belong to Agricom and that all the consideration (including the consideration for the inventive activity and the assignment of the related IP rights) have been duly received by Elettrotek.

In any case, we suggest including appropriate R&Ws covering this matter (incl. ownership of the IP rights over the plants’ drawings).

Agricom and D&G – Wastewater discharge

Based on the Reviewed Documentation, the wastewater streams generated at the Fossalta Plants are (i) sanitary wastewater, discharged into the public sewage system; and (ii) stormwater runoff, discharged into the Colatore Zona Industriale Fossalta Channel without any previous treatment.

Pursuant to art. 39, para. 3 of the Veneto Water Protection Regulation (Piano di Tutela delle Acque), the first flush rainwater (acque meteoriche di prima pioggia, di dilavamento e di lavaggio) concerning yards (piazzali) with an extension equal to more than 5,000 sq.m. shall be collected, treated and subject to a wastewater discharge authorization.

In this respect, based on the Reviewed Documentation and as also confirmed by the Environmental Report:

the Fossalta Plants are operated by both Agricom and D&G and are interested by a common yard with an extension equal to approximately 9,000 sq.m.;

each of the two companies operates a portion of the common yard with an extension equal to less than 5,000 sq.m., so no wastewater discharge authorization was deemed necessary;

however, the yard is used and shared between the two companies without any physical separation or constraint, so that is not possible to assess whether the 5,000 sq.m. limit is respected; and

therefore, the Fossalta Plants seem to fall under the provisions of the afore-mentioned art. 39, para. 3 of the Veneto Water Protection Regulation, thus requiring the issuance of a wastewater discharge authorization by the competent Province regarding the first flush rainwater. In this respect, pursuant to art. 133 and 137 of the Environmental Code, the absence of the prescribed wastewater discharge authorization may result in both administrative fines and criminal sanctions.

We suggest applying with the Province of Venice as soon as possible in order to be granted the relevant wastewater discharge authorization, as well as evaluating with a technical advisor whether is necessary to install a rainwater collection tank and perform the related sewage works.

Moreover, in any case, we suggest including appropriate special indemnity in the Agreement.

Data Protection

Main Findings

Action/Recommendation

Companies - Lack of GDPR documentation

The Reviewed Documentation does not include some of the documentation required to ensure and demonstrate compliance with the GDPR. Specifically, the Companies have not provided the following documentation:

privacy policy for (i) collaborators, (ii) external contractors, and (iii) visitors;

documentation related to the Companies’ internal data governance structure (e.g., appointment of persons authorized to process personal data other than for the activity of CV management);

internal data protection policies/procedures (e.g., procedure for the management of data subjects’ rights, policy on the storage of personal data, procedure on the management of personal data breaches cd. data breach, policy on the use of IT tools);

information signs regarding the processing of personal data using video surveillance systems;

agreements with data processors pursuant to Art. 28 GDPR;

data controller’s legitimate interest assessments (“LIAs”) for the following data processing activities: (i) ensuring the proper functioning of the Companies’ websites and carrying out anonymous statistics on their use, as outlined in the privacy notices; (ii) recording of images through video surveillance systems; (iii) processing geolocalisation data of the vehicles driven by their employees; and (iv) managing the Companies’ servers.

The lack of such documentation could indicate a lack of an adequate privacy governance under the GDPR and therefore exposes the Companies to the risk of GDPR Sanctions.

We recommend providing an indemnification obligation to cover (i) the costs and expenses arising from any GDPR Sanctions and (ii) the costs arising from the implementation (in the period immediately following the Envisaged Transaction) of a privacy governance implementation project.

The process to bring the Companies into compliance with the provisions of the GDPR may have an impact on its operations and IT systems. It is, therefore, a project that may prove challenging not only from the perspective of the legal fees, but also because of the costs related to the Companies’ operational process and IT systems.

Companies – Joint controllership agreement

The Companies have signed a joint controllership agreement pursuant to Article 26 GDPR since they both make use of:

“digital storage spaces (servers and management);

e-mail server and related domain “gruppodaniel”;

shift clocking portal (provided and managed by the same external supplier appointed as data controller with an attachment to the service contract);

video surveillance system”.

According to Article 26 GDPR joint controllership exists in case two controllers jointly determine the purposes and means of personal data processing.

However, the Reviewed Documentation shows that for the activities of their respective competence the Companies act as autonomous data controllers. As a matter of fact, even though D&G uses infrastructures (e.g., video surveillance system, servers) owned by Agricom, the Companies do not jointly determine the purposes and means of the processing.

Indeed, from the Review Documentation it seems that D&G has merely outsourced to Agricom the abovementioned processing activities, with the result that Agricom processes personal data on behalf of D&G’s, consequently acting as data processor pursuant to Article 28 GDPR.

Incorrect attribution of privacy roles of the Companies (i.e., joint controllers instead of data controller and processor) could result in a violation of Article 28 GDPR, and thus expose the Companies to GDPR Sanctions.

We suggest providing an indemnification obligation covering any costs and expenses arising from possible GDPR Sanctions.

In any case, we suggest including in the Agreement a pre-closing undertaking to formally appoint Agricom as D&G’s data processor for the activities listed in the joint controllership agreement (Data Processing Agreement, “DPA”). The DPA shall replace the joint controllership agreement currently in force.

Companies – Shift stamping data

Based on the Reviewed Documentation (i.e., employees privacy notices and relevant DPIAs) we understand that the Companies collect their employees’ shift stamps data (“timbratura di inizio e fine turno di lavoro”) via a mobile phone application which requires them to turn on geolocalisation to check in and out. The activation of geolocalisation is required not only when employees work on site but also when they work remotely.

The collection of geolocalisation data is lawful only if limited to when the employee is close to the workplace, for instance because the employee chooses to check in/out using such a system. Since such processing is highly intrusive, the Italian data protection authority has highlighted that such a system to collect shift stamps data must be used as an alternative to more traditional systems (see doc. web n. 5497522).

Therefore, the system adopted by the Companies for the collection of shift stamps data, by mandatorily requiring the collection of geolocalisation data, might result in a violation of the proportionality and minimization principles set out under Article 5 GDPR, thus exposing the Companies to the risk of GDPR Sanctions.

We suggest providing an indemnification obligation covering any costs and expenses arising from possible GDPR Sanctions.

In any case, we suggest including in the Agreement a pre-closing undertaking to minimise the categories of personal data collected by the Companies to record shift stamping in order to comply with Article 5 GDPR.

Agricom – Monitoring of employees’ company emails

Agricom’s employment contracts are not compliant with the Guidelines on the monitoring of the employees’ company emails by the employer issued by the Italian Data Protection Authority on March 5th, 2007 (“Guidelines”).

Agricom’s employment contracts provide that:

“Correspondence and files handled by the [company’s] computer must be related to [the employee’s] job performance. Private correspondence will not be allowed on the employee’s company email. The company also reserves the right to view email received and sent, as well as files contained on the employee’s computer, as these are company information and tools.”

The Guidelines state that employers might monitor their employees’ correspondence through the company email address only under exceptional circumstances and that they must regulate the employees’ use of the company’s IT tools (such as computers) through a specific corporate procedure which must be made available to all employees beforehand.

Therefore, Agricom’s employment contract is in contrast with the Guidelines. Moreover, the Reviewed Documentation does not include any procedure on the use of the Companies’ IT tools.

Consequently, the abovementioned provision in the employment contract might constitute a violation of the principles of proportionality and/or transparency set out in Articles 5 and 13 GDPR and thus expose Agricom to GDPR Sanctions.

We suggest providing an indemnification obligation covering any costs and expenses arising from possible GDPR Sanctions.

In any case, we suggest including in the Agreement a pre-closing undertaking to amend Agricom’s employment contract and to adopt a corporate procedure on the use of the company’s IT tools in order to comply with Articles 5 and 13 GDPR as well as with the Guidelines.

Companies – Retention of video surveillance data

The retention period indicated in the video surveillance information notice of both Companies (i.e., three days) differs from the one indicated in the relevant data processing impact assessments (DPIAs) provided by the Companies (i.e., seven days).

Therefore, it is unclear which retention period ultimately applies to images collected by the Companies through the video surveillance system.

This could result in a non-compliance with the principle of transparency and/or of lawfulness set out in Articles 5 and 13 GDPR, and thus expose the Company to GDPR Sanctions.

We suggest providing an indemnification obligation covering any costs and expenses arising from possible GDPR Sanctions.

In any case, we suggest including in the Agreement a pre-closing undertaking to make the video surveillance information notice and DPIAs consistent with each other in order to comply with Articles 5 and 13 GDPR.

Companies – Website privacy policy

The Companies’ website privacy policies do not provide the website users with complete information according to Article 13 GDPR and are not transparent. In particular:

the legal basis for processing personal data sent to the Companies via the contact form on their websites is not correctly identified (i.e., consent instead of performing pre-contractual actions at the request of users); and

Agricom’s website privacy policy refers to a processing activity (newsletter) that does not seem to take place from the analysis of the website.

This could result in a non-compliance with the principle of transparency set out in Articles 5 and 13 GDPR, and thus expose the Companies to GDPR Sanctions.

We suggest providing an indemnification obligation covering any costs and expenses arising from possible GDPR Sanctions.

In any case, we suggest including in the Agreement a pre-closing undertaking to update the Companies’ websites privacy policies in order to comply with Articles 5 and 13 GDPR.

Companies – Cookie policy

The Companies’ cookie policies do not provide users with all the information outlined by the Italian Data Protection Authority in the Guidelines on cookies and other tracking tools issued on 10 June 2021. In particular:

the cookie banners refer to the use of categories of cookies that are not mentioned in the cookie policies; and

the cookie policies lack the information required by the abovementioned guidelines issued by the Italian data protection authority (e.g., the list of specific cookies used by the website and their storage periods).

This could result in a non-compliance with the principle of transparency set out in Articles 5 and 13 GDPR, and thus expose the Companies to GDPR Sanctions.

We suggest providing an indemnification obligation covering any costs and expenses arising from possible GDPR Sanctions.

In any case, we suggest including in the Agreement a pre-closing undertaking to update the Companies’ cookie policies and banners in order to comply with Articles 5 and 13 GDPR.

Companies – Privacy notices

The privacy notices provided by the Companies are not fully compliant with the principle of transparency set out in Articles 5 and 13 GDPR. In particular:

the Companies’ privacy notices for employees do not clearly specify the legal basis and purpose of each data processing activity;

D&G’s privacy notice for employees does not clarify the purposes for the tracking activities the company carries out on the vehicles driven by its employees (e.g., GPS tracking, tachographs);

the Companies’ privacy notices for clients and suppliers refer to an incorrect legal basis for the processing of the clients’ personal data (i.e., consent instead of the performance of a contract or of pre-contractual measures explicitly requested by the data subject); and

the Companies’ privacy notices for candidates refer to an incorrect legal basis for the processing of candidates’ personal data (i.e., consent instead of the performance of a contract or of pre-contractual measures explicitly requested by the data subject), and thus incorrectly require candidates to consent to the processing of their personal data.

This could result in a non-compliance with the principle of transparency set out in Articles 5 and 13 GDPR, and thus expose the Companies to GDPR Sanctions.

We suggest providing an indemnification obligation covering any costs and expenses arising from possible GDPR Sanctions.

In any case, we suggest including in the Agreement a pre-closing undertaking to update the Companies’ information notices for their employees, candidates, and clients and suppliers in order to comply with Articles 5 and 13 GDPR.

Companies – Record of processing activities

The records of processing activities pursuant Article 30 GDPR kept by both Companies as data controllers do not provide clear and accurate information on the personal data processing activities carried out by the Companies.

In particular, such records:

describe some processing activities in such a broad way that it is not possible to clearly identify what is meant (e.g., “servers’ management”);

still refer to monitoring of covid-19 green passes, even though it is stated such processing has ceased since March 31st, 2022;

list more than one lawful basis for each processing activity;

only include identification data among the categories of processed personal data;

in some instances refer to “natural persons” as a category of data subjects, instead of e.g. clients; and

include the Companies’ internal personnel among the categories of recipients of the processed personal data.

Such inaccuracies might result in a violation of Article 30 GDPR and expose the Companies to GDPR Sanctions.

We suggest providing an indemnification obligation covering any costs and expenses arising from possible GDPR Sanctions.

In any case, we suggest including in the Agreement a pre-closing undertaking to update the Companies’ records of processing activities in order to comply with Article 30 GDPR.

Companies’ relationships with main customers – general remarks

Agricom’s commercial relationships with its main customers are generally governed by: (i) sales agreements formalised by entering each relevant order into the system and sending the customer an order confirmation; and (ii) orders that can be linked to a specific commercial agreement that sets out the price and quality of the goods. The VDR includes a list of Agricom’s top-10 customers (whose names appear to have been redacted) and a copy of the legal documentation that regulates commercial relations only with Customer A (documentation which appears only partial), Customer C and Customer J.[28]

Based on the Reviewed Documentation and Received Information, we understand that:

there is no documentation available from the company regarding the other main customers, given that Agricom concludes most of its sales agreements by telephone and enters all information collected during these calls directly into the system to start production; and

when Agricom formalises a commercial sales relationship through an order and order confirmation, Agricom does not impose its own general T&Cs of sale and does not accept the purchase conditions provided by each individual customer. Therefore, these relationships are poorly regulated from a legal standpoint (i.e., absence of structured general conditions of purchase or sale).

Because of the peculiarity of the market in which Agricom operates, procurement or sales relationships – despite the absence of relationships with agents or business finders – are often entered into with the assistance of business agent intermediaries (agenti di affari in mediazione). Relationships with business agent intermediaries are formalised through documents that summarise the main conditions (e.g., goods, delivery and payment methods, reference to the general T&Cs valid for standard national contracts in force at the Italian commodity exchanges) governing the agreement between Agricom and the final customer (or supplier), as well as any amounts paid to the business agent intermediary.

Regarding D&G’s commercial relationships, Agricom is its main customer given that the services provided to Agricom amount to approx. 87% of all business carried out annually by D&G. Therefore, relationships with third-party customers take on a residual nature.

According to the Received Information: (i) no other agreements governing long-term relationships are missing; and (ii) all the different contractual models that Agricom uses with its main customers have been provided. These relationships raise no major issues from a legal standpoint and do not appear to be governed by provisions that would be triggered by the Envisaged Transaction.

For information purposes only.

when Agricom formalises a supply relationship through a purchase order and order confirmation, Agricom does not impose its own general purchase T&Cs.

However, if D&G is unable to carry out the service requested by Agricom, D&G commissions the transport and logistics service to a third party, who issues an invoice directly to D&G, who in turn invoices Agricom for all amounts requested by the third party as consideration for their services. Please note that we are not in a position (i) to ascertain whether the fitness-for-use has been attested for the entire assets in which Agricom operates and (ii) to assess whether what is attested by the afore-mentioned documentation represents the actual de facto state of such assets, since such assessments depend on technical matters and site visits.

Agricom - Flexibility clause

The Reviewed Documentation includes a copy of a permanent part-time contract of an Agricom employee which includes a clause that gives the employer flexibility to adjust working hours. Under this clause, the employer may request the employee, by giving at least 2 days’ notice, to: (i) work the same hours, but with varying shift patterns; and/or (ii) extend the number of working hours.

However, under the NCBA Trade, this employment contract must indicate the technical, organisational, productive or replacement reasons authorising the use of the above clause.

Because this contract does not indicate these reasons, a risk exists of the above clause being considered void.

We are unaware whether any other employees have this clause in their employment contracts.

We suggest including in the Agreement an adequate set of R&Ws regarding compliance with labour laws.

Additionally, as for the future, we suggest modifying the flexibility clause in compliance with the law.

Agricom – registration under Regulation (EC) No. 183/2005

Regulation (EC) No 183/2005 lays down (a) general rules on feed (mangimi) hygiene; (b) conditions and arrangements ensuring traceability of feed; (c) conditions and arrangements for registration and approval of feed establishments and plant.

According to Art. 9 of the above Regulation, feed business operators shall:

notify the appropriate competent authority of any establishments under their control, active in any of the stages of production, processing, storage, transport or distribution of feed; and

provide the competent authority with up-to-date information on any establishments under their control as referred to in point (a), including notifying the competent authority of any significant change in activities and any closure of an existing establishment.

Based on the Reviewed Documentation, the Company is regularly registered under said Regulation, regarding both the Fossalta Plants and the Monastier Plants.

For information purposes only.
